// BAD — every new shape means editing this function.
double area(dynamic shape) {
  if (shape is Circle) return 3.14 * shape.r * shape.r;
  if (shape is Square) return shape.s * shape.s;
  // Tomorrow: Triangle? Come back and modify this. Every shape = 1 change here.
  throw 'Unknown shape';
}

// GOOD — adding a Shape subclass requires ZERO changes here.
abstract class Shape { double area(); }
class Circle extends Shape { ... @override double area() => 3.14*r*r; }
class Square extends Shape { ... @override double area() => s*s; }
double area(Shape shape) => shape.area();
// Add Triangle tomorrow → no changes to this function.

sections.markdown:
**The classic LSP violation — Square extends Rectangle:**

```dart
class Rectangle { double w, h; setW(double w) {...} setH(double h) {...} }
class Square extends Rectangle {
  @override setW(double w) { super.w = w; super.h = w; }   // keep it square!
  @override setH(double h) { super.w = h; super.h = h; }
}

void caller(Rectangle r) {
  r.setW(3); r.setH(4);
  assert(r.w * r.h == 12);   // ← FAILS if r is actually a Square!
}
```

Square *should* be a Rectangle. But it breaks callers' expectations. This is why 'is-a' relationships must include *behavioral compatibility*, not just field compatibility.

**Fix:** Don't make Square extend Rectangle. Model them as separate implementations of a `Shape` interface.

